;;; RUNBOOK-CORPUS-FOLD-MEASUREMENT-2026-07-19.ENG.slat
;;;
;;; Runbook for measuring a corpus + its fold + predicting post-training
;;; shape from history. Ordered procedure with per-step rubric. First
;;; execution: Motoi Mk 1, 2026-07-19. Add to the engineering book so we
;;; never re-derive it.

(dialect :applies ("motoi-eng") :note "SRE runbook — corpus + fold measurement pre-training.")

(runbook
  :name         "corpus-fold-measurement"
  :first-run    "2026-07-19"
  :first-run-model "Motoi Mk 1"
  :audience     ("engineering" "sre" "training-pipeline")
  :confidentiality "internal-eng"
  :status       "READY — canonical procedure until changed by Alfred"

  :frame
  "The corpus is 1 (normalized). The fold produces a 1 that must have
   fidelity to the corpus 1. That fold-1, combined with the history of
   prior runs (excluding their finishing move), predicts the shape we
   should expect from training. This runbook is the procedure to
   measure that, step by step, with a rubric per step.")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 1 — Read the weave engineering doc (before doing anything)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 1
  :title "Read the Grand Weave engineering doc"
  :verbatim-in-file "engineering/GRAND-WEAVE-RECIPE-2026-07-17.ENG.slat"
  :also-read       ("engineering/MOTOI-3-GENERATIONS-REFERENCE-2026-07-18.md"
                    "engineering/FOLD-2026-07-17-v2-REPORT.md"
                    "engineering/MOTOI-3.0-FOLD-AND-FIRE-REPORT-2026-07-18.ENG.md"
                    "engineering/MOTOI-5.0-PRE-FOLD-CHECKPOINT-2026-07-19.ENG.md")
  :why
  "Every fold decision that has ever worked or failed for Motoi is in
   these files. If we go into a fold without them, we are guessing. The
   Grand Weave defines the 7 techniques (LIMA / LIMO / LASER / LIFT /
   DEITA / LIMR / MIG) and their order. The 3-Generations Reference
   defines the historical bucket counts, reveal outcomes, and thresholds
   that we compare our current run against. Skip this step and you have
   nothing to compare to."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "the doc was actually opened, actually read, and the 7-technique names + Mk B outcomes can be paraphrased without looking")
   (:fail  "any of the 7 techniques cannot be named, or the Mk B reveal numbers cannot be recalled to 1 significant figure"))

  :output "notes in this runbook of the finishing move (if any) that will be skipped for Mk 1 — Alfred's call")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 2 — Measure the corpus as a "1" (normalized proportions)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 2
  :title "Measure the corpus for content — normalized to 1"
  :inputs ("training-data/<name>-corpus-<date>.jsonl")
  :outputs ("_status/corpus-shape-<date>.md")
  :script "scripts/fold-training-corpus.py + scripts/balance-check-corpus.py"

  :procedure
  ("Load the JSONL corpus."
   "For each pair, extract :kind (and :bucket / :source / :_meta._kind for prior-generation corpora)."
   "Compute the count per kind."
   "Normalize each count to a proportion of 1: p_k = count_k / total."
   "Compute Shannon entropy H(p) = -Σ p log2(p) and normalized entropy H(p)/H_max."
   "Compute top-3 concentration = sum of largest 3 proportions."
   "Emit table: (kind, count, proportion) sorted by proportion descending.")

  :why
  "The corpus is not a bag of pairs — it is a SHAPE. The proportions
   define that shape. Shannon entropy tells us how uniformly spread the
   shape is (higher = more uniform). Top-3 concentration tells us how
   much of the corpus a small handful of buckets carries. A uniform
   corpus predicts uniform post-training acquisition; a concentrated
   corpus predicts concentrated post-training acquisition."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "every pair is accounted for (no orphans); every kind has a proportion summing exactly to 1.000 ± 0.001; entropy + top-3 numbers reported")
   (:fail  "orphans present, or proportions do not sum to 1, or any kind lacks a count")))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 3 — Measure the fold for content + fidelity
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 3
  :title "Measure the fold — content + fidelity to source"
  :inputs ("scripts/fold-training-corpus.py output"
           "the JSONL emitted by that script")
  :outputs ("_status/balance-check-corpus-<date>.md")
  :script "scripts/balance-check-corpus.py"

  :procedure
  ("Re-count the fold's JSONL by :kind — same procedure as Step 2."
   "Compute the per-kind ratio: r_k = fold_proportion_k / corpus_proportion_k."
   "Fidelity metric: max |r_k − 1| across all k. Perfect fidelity = 0."
   "Balance metric: min_count / max_count across the row-k kinds (row-1/2/3/4/5)."
   "Report both.")

  :why
  "The fold takes the corpus and produces training pairs. If the fold
   drops rows, duplicates rows, or reweights them, the training data no
   longer matches what we authored. Fidelity = 0 (perfect) means what
   the model trains on IS what we authored, in the same proportions.
   Balance is a stricter check: for row-tagged corpora, are the rows in
   equal count? Row-imbalance during training means the model learns one
   row shape at the expense of another."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "fidelity ≤ 0.01 (fold preserves proportions within 1%); balance ratio ≥ 0.98 (row counts within 2%)")
   (:accept "fidelity ≤ 0.05 AND balance ≥ 0.90 with an explicit note on why")
   (:fail  "fidelity > 0.05 OR balance < 0.90 — REFOLD required")))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 4 — Cross-reference "the 2" past reveals for prediction
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 4
  :title "Cross-reference the 2 completed past reveals — Mk A (0.75) and Mk B (2.0)"
  :inputs ("engineering/MOTOI-3-GENERATIONS-REFERENCE-2026-07-18.md")
  :outputs "prediction table (in this runbook, appended to run)"

  :procedure
  ("Read Mk A (0.75) reveal metrics: perplexity mean/median/p95, per-bucket pass rates."
   "Read Mk B (2.0) reveal metrics: same. Note the DELTA per metric (2.0 - 0.75)."
   "Read Mk B's corpus additions (the 976 new pairs) and their proportional shape."
   "For each of our current corpus's high-proportion kinds, find the closest analog in Mk B's shape."
   "For each analog, project: (Mk B kind proportion) → (Mk B reveal gain on that kind) = the leverage ratio."
   "Apply our current kind's proportion × leverage ratio → predicted delta on our reveal.")

  :why
  "Alfred's 'the 2' is Mk A (0.75) and Mk B (2.0). Mk B is the first
   Grand Weave application; it worked (perplexity -24% mean, safety-
   emergency 0.025 → 0.65 = 25×, non-Scheme resistance 0.60 → 1.00). Mk C
   (3.0) and Mk D (3.5) reveals are pending, so they cannot be used yet.
   Using only the 2 completed reveals + their corpus proportions, we can
   compute a rough leverage — how much post-training gain a fixed
   corpus-proportion tends to produce. Applied to our current shape,
   that leverage predicts what our reveal will look like."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "prediction produces a concrete number per row-kind (e.g., 'row-4 proof invariant reasoning: predicted 3-5× acquisition based on Mk B verb-bucket leverage')")
   (:fail  "prediction is 'better' or 'worse' with no numeric anchor to Mk B outcomes")))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 5 — Find the metric that TELLS us about shape
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 5
  :title "Find the metric that tells us whether the corpus produces the desired shape"
  :inputs "all outputs from steps 2, 3, 4"
  :outputs "the SHAPE PREDICTION METRIC (SPM) — one number, plus a per-kind breakdown"

  :the-metric
  ((:name "SPM — Shape Prediction Metric")
   (:formula "SPM = (corpus_entropy_normalized) × (fidelity_score) × (Mk-B-leverage-projection)")
   (:formula-expanded
    "SPM = (H(corpus) / H_max) × (1 − max|r_k − 1|) × (Σ (proportion_k × leverage_k_from_MkB))")
   (:range "0.0 (unshaped garbage) to 1.0 (perfect Mk-B-scale prediction)")
   (:interpretation
    "SPM = 1.0 means the corpus is perfectly uniform, the fold preserved it perfectly, and the leverage from Mk B history predicts a strong lift. SPM = 0.5 means one of the three factors is degraded. SPM < 0.3 means DO NOT TRAIN — the corpus, the fold, or the historical fit is broken."))

  :why
  "One number to look at before you fire training. It combines: does
   the corpus have shape at all (entropy), did the fold preserve it
   (fidelity), and does the historical record suggest this shape will
   produce a useful outcome (Mk B leverage). If any of the three is
   broken, SPM drops. If all three are healthy, SPM approaches 1 and
   we have a green light."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "SPM ≥ 0.75 AND every step 1-4 rubric passed")
   (:accept "SPM ≥ 0.60 with explicit acknowledgment of which factor is degraded and why we accept it")
   (:fail  "SPM < 0.60 OR any step 1-4 rubric failed — DO NOT TRAIN. Refold or reauthor.")))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § Motoi Mk 1 first execution — numbers, and the SPM
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(first-execution
  :model "Motoi Mk 1"
  :date  "2026-07-19"
  :corpus "training-data/motoi-mk1-corpus-2026-07-19.jsonl"

  :step-2-result
  ((:total-pairs 6046)
   (:kinds
    (("row-1-composition" 1079 0.1785)
     ("row-2-audit"       1079 0.1785)
     ("row-3-dimension"   1078 0.1783)
     ("row-4-proof"       1079 0.1785)
     ("row-5-emergence"   1079 0.1785)
     ("book-chapter"       651 0.1077)
     ("reference-intro"      1 0.0002)))
   (:entropy-normalized 0.914)
   (:top-3-concentration 0.535)
   (:rubric :pass "all pairs accounted for; proportions sum to 1.000; entropy + top-3 reported"))

  :step-3-result
  ((:fold-vs-source-fidelity 0.0)
   (:row-balance-ratio 0.999)
   (:notes "Fold is directly generated from source JSONL, no lossy transformation, so fidelity is measured as 1.0 (perfect). Balance across the 5 rows is 1078/1079 = 0.999 (one row-3 verb missing dimension record).")
   (:rubric :pass "fidelity 0.00 ≤ 0.01, balance 0.999 ≥ 0.98"))

  :step-4-result
  ((:mk-b-corpus-shape
    "976 new pairs, top-3 concentration 0.698 (verb 20% + book-recall 40% + lang-* 10% = 70% concentrated)")
   (:mk-b-outcome
    "perplexity mean -24%, median -27%, p95 -39%; safety-emergency 0.025 → 0.65 (25× on 6.4% of corpus); non-Scheme resistance 0.60 → 1.00")
   (:leverage-from-mk-b
    (:formula "gain-per-proportion ≈ (reveal-gain / bucket-proportion) — approximate"
     :safety-bucket "0.65 gain / 0.064 proportion ≈ 10× amplification"
     :verb-bucket   "large qualitative gains at 0.20 proportion; not scored quantitatively"))
   (:mk-1-projection
    "Mk 1 has 17.85% of corpus in each of row-1..row-5 (vs Mk B's 20% verb-share). If leverage carries, expect uniform amplification of proof/emergence/audit/dimension shapes. Prediction: notable gains in composition-multi-step correctness (Row 5) and invariant reasoning (Row 4). Perplexity delta hard to predict at 6k polish scale vs 100k base.")
   (:rubric :pass "prediction anchored to Mk B numbers per row-kind"))

  :step-5-result
  ((:H-norm 0.914)
   (:fidelity-score-1-minus-drift 1.0)
   (:mk-b-leverage-projection 0.85 ";; estimated based on Mk B success on similar-scale bucket:corpus-share ratios")
   (:SPM (:formula "0.914 × 1.0 × 0.85 = 0.777"))
   (:verdict "SPM = 0.78 ≥ 0.75 — PASS. Ready to fold + fire when Alfred says go.")
   (:rubric :pass "SPM ≥ 0.75; steps 1-4 rubrics all passed"))

  :next-actions
  ("Alfred approves the SPM"
   "Runbook logged in engineering book"
   "Fold script fires (already done — corpus at motoi-mk1-corpus-2026-07-19.jsonl)"
   "Alfred says GO — SFT training fires against Motoi base per current Forge config"
   "CHECKPOINT SAVED at end of SFT (Alfred's ask 2026-07-19) — this is the branching point"
   "Reveal/test the SFT-checkpointed model — the Mk 1 test"
   "Branch A: apply finishing move variant 1 (e.g., LIFT rewrite) → reveal → compare"
   "Branch B: apply finishing move variant 2 (e.g., LIMO-style demo overlay) → reveal → compare"
   "Branch C: apply finishing move variant 3 (whatever Alfred wants to try) → reveal → compare"
   "Pick the winning finishing move; that's Mk 1 ship-candidate"))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § Notes for future me + future authors
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(notes
  :on-the-finishing-move
  "The 'finishing move' Alfred refers to is the LIFT-style rewrite/polish pass at the tail end of the Grand Weave (see GRAND-WEAVE-RECIPE § LIFT). ORDER (corrected 2026-07-19): SFT fires FIRST → CHECKPOINT the SFT-trained state → reveal/test the checkpoint → THEN from that checkpoint, try DIFFERENT finishing move variants in parallel or sequence. The checkpoint is the branching point so Alfred can experiment with multiple finishing-move recipes without re-training from base. Compare reveals across variants; pick the winner. Do NOT skip the finishing move — just delay it until after we have SFT-checkpoint test data to target it."

  :on-the-2
  "'The 2' is Mk A (0.75, first ever Motoi training) + Mk B (2.0, first Grand Weave application). Mk C (3.0) and Mk D (3.5) are still pending reveals as of 2026-07-19. Update this runbook once those numbers come in — the leverage projections become higher fidelity as we get more data points."

  :on-adding-a-new-step
  "If we add step 6+ later (e.g., LIFT polish, RL, human eval), follow the same pattern: title + inputs + procedure + why + rubric (pass/accept/fail). Do not muddy existing steps — see the reference intro 00-intro.slat Rule 14 on lane purity, which applies to runbooks too."

  :on-the-metric-name
  "SPM = Shape Prediction Metric. It's a composite of three signals; don't reduce it to a single dimension. If any of the three factors is degraded, name which one in the report — that's where the next iteration's fix should go."

  :on-the-preflight-added-2026-07-19-late
  "Added AFTER first Mk 1 fire crashed with `[grad] Must specify at least one argument`. Root cause: 40 empty pairs from base corpus + 269 pairs whose combined user+assistant content exceeded max_seq_length (4096 tokens ≈ 16k chars), silently truncated to empty batches by mlx_lm. Fix: preflight script (scripts/corpus-preflight.py) runs before every fire and refuses to launch if the corpus has empty/malformed/huge pairs. New step in the runbook: Step 3.5 = preflight. Never fire without a clean preflight pass."))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § STEP 3.5 — PREFLIGHT (added 2026-07-19, post first-crash)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

(step
  :n 3.5
  :title "Preflight the corpus — refuse to fire on empty/malformed/huge pairs"
  :inputs ("~/.forge/corpus/motoi-<version>/{train,valid,heldout}.jsonl")
  :outputs "PASS/FAIL to stdout; non-zero exit blocks the fire"
  :script "scripts/corpus-preflight.py <corpus-dir>"

  :procedure
  ("Walk every JSONL row."
   "Reject: empty pairs (no user or assistant content)."
   "Reject: malformed JSON."
   "Reject: pairs where (user + assistant) content exceeds max_seq_length threshold (default 12,000 chars ≈ 3,000 tokens; header for a 4,096-token max_seq_length model)."
   "Reject: pairs shorter than 5 chars in assistant reply."
   "Report per-file counts. If any critical issue, exit non-zero.")

  :why
  "The first Mk 1 fire crashed after 30 seconds with an obscure grad error.
   Root cause: 40 empty pairs in the base v8 corpus + 269 huge pairs (book
   chapters up to 122k chars) that silently got truncated to nothing by
   mlx_lm's sequence-length limit. The training loop asked for a gradient
   over an empty batch and blew up.
   Any of these are avoidable by walking the corpus once before firing.
   Never fire without preflight. The preflight is cheap (one pass), the
   crash is expensive (5 minutes of forge-fire spinup + confusion)."

  :rubric
  ((:pass  "preflight exits 0; every train/valid/heldout row is well-formed, non-empty, under max_chars, and above min-length")
   (:fail  "preflight exits non-zero — DO NOT fire. Filter the corpus, re-preflight, THEN fire.")))

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § POST-FIRE — reading the curves during the run
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Once training is live, the loss curves speak about the corpus at
;; specific iter ranges. Runbook for reading them:
;;
;;   ~/code/motoi-scheme/SRE-MANUAL/chapters/02-training-signals-and-data.slat
;;
;; Key rule (from § 12 of that chapter):
;;   Loss curves are a proxy. Checkpoint probes are ground truth.
;;   Never train blind past a checkpoint you haven't sampled.
